  "problem_spec": {
    "title": "Synchronized p-adic valuations with an order constraint and 2-adic coupling",
    "objects": [
      "For primes p, v_p denotes the p-adic valuation.",
      "All bases a are integers > 1; modular arithmetic is standard.",
      "n is a positive integer to be determined (least such n)."
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "Use LTE for odd primes p with a ≡ 1 (mod p).",
      "Use LTE for odd p with a ≡ −1 (mod p) requiring n even.",
      "Use the 2-adic LTE for odd a.",
      "Use multiplicative orders modulo prime powers and the non-Wieferich status of 11 for base 2."
    ],
    "tasks": [
      "Determine the least positive integer n satisfying the five simultaneous conditions in the statement."
    ],
    "prohibited_shortcuts": [
      "Do not assume (Z/2^kZ)^× is cyclic for k ≥ 3.",
      "Do not use probabilistic guessing or brute-force search over n; reasoning must pass via valuations/orders.",
      "Do not assert p^2 ∣ a^{ord_p(a)} − 1 without verification (avoid Wieferich pitfalls)."
    ]
  },
  "theorem_refs": [
    {
      "name": "Lifting The Exponent (LTE) for odd primes",
      "statement": "If p is odd, p | (a − 1), and n ≥ 1, then v_p(a^n − 1) = v_p(a − 1) + v_p(n).",
      "source": "LeVeque, Topics in Number Theory, Vol. I, §6.3; Nathanson, GTM 195, Thm 6.2"
    },
    {
      "name": "LTE for a ≡ −1 (mod p), n even",
      "statement": "If p is odd, p ∤ a, a ≡ −1 (mod p), and n is even, then v_p(a^n − 1) = v_p(a + 1) + v_p(n).",
      "source": "Common LTE variants; see Andreescu–Andrica; AoPS LTE compendium"
    },
    {
      "name": "2-adic LTE",
      "statement": "For odd a and n ≥ 1: if n is odd, v_2(a^n − 1) = v_2(a − 1); if n is even, v_2(a^n − 1) = v_2(a − 1) + v_2(a + 1) + v_2(n) − 1.",
      "source": "Evan Chen, Orders of 2 in Differences of Odd Powers; Zaĭtsev, Mathematical Notes (1995)"
    },
    {
      "name": "Multiplicative order lifting modulo prime powers",
      "statement": "If p ∤ a and t = ord_p(a) with p^2 ∤ a^t − 1, then ord_{p^k}(a) = t for all k ≥ 1; moreover v_p(a^{tn} − 1) = v_p(a^t − 1) + v_p(n) for odd p.",
      "source": "Ireland & Rosen, §4.7 (Lemma 4.14)"
    },
    {
      "name": "Structure of units modulo 2^k",
      "statement": "(Z/2^kZ)^× ≅ C_2 × C_{2^{k−2}} for k ≥ 3; ord_{2^k}(3) = ord_{2^k}(5) = 2^{k−2}.",
      "source": "Ireland & Rosen, Thm 2.5.3; Niven–Zuckerman–Montgomery, Ch. 5.3"
    },
    {
      "name": "Chinese Remainder Theorem (constructive)",
      "statement": "For pairwise coprime moduli, simultaneous congruences have a unique solution modulo the product; explicit inverses construct solutions.",
      "source": "Rosen, Elementary Number Theory, §4.3"
    },
    {
      "name": "Non-Wieferich status of 11 for base 2",
      "statement": "11 is not Wieferich to base 2: 2^{10} ≢ 1 (mod 11^2). Consequently, v_11(2^{10k} − 1) = 1 + v_11(k).",
      "source": "McIntosh–Roettger (2007); OEIS A001220; elementary computation 2^{10} ≡ 56 (mod 121) ≠ 1"
    }
  ],
  "problem_pair": {
    "problem_text": "Let v_p denote the p-adic valuation. Find the least positive integer n satisfying simultaneously the following five conditions:\n(1) v_3(10^n − 1) = 4.\n(2) v_5(6^n − 1) = 3.\n(3) v_7(20^n − 1) = 3.\n(4) v_2(3^n − 1) = 7.\n(5) 11 divides 2^n − 1 but 11^2 does not divide 2^n − 1.\nYour answer should be a single explicit integer n.",
    "solution_text": "We solve each condition using LTE and order considerations, then combine them.\n\n(1) For p = 3 with a = 10, 3 | (10 − 1) and 3 ∤ 10. By LTE (odd p, a ≡ 1 mod p): v_3(10^n − 1) = v_3(10 − 1) + v_3(n) = v_3(9) + v_3(n) = 2 + v_3(n). The requirement v_3(10^n − 1) = 4 gives v_3(n) = 2, i.e., 9 | n and 27 ∤ n.\n\n(2) For p = 5 with a = 6, 5 | (6 − 1) and 5 ∤ 6. LTE yields v_5(6^n − 1) = v_5(6 − 1) + v_5(n) = 1 + v_5(n) = 3, so v_5(n) = 2, i.e., 25 | n and 125 ∤ n.\n\n(3) For p = 7 with a = 20 ≡ −1 (mod 7). If n were odd then 20^n ≡ −1 (mod 7) and 7 ∤ (20^n − 1), contradicting the required positive valuation. So n is even. By LTE for odd p with a ≡ −1 (mod p) and even n: v_7(20^n − 1) = v_7(20 + 1) + v_7(n) = v_7(21) + v_7(n) = 1 + v_7(n). The target v_7(20^n − 1) = 3 implies v_7(n) = 2, i.e., 49 | n and 343 ∤ n.\n\n(4) For p = 2 with a = 3 odd. If n were odd then v_2(3^n − 1) = v_2(3 − 1) = 1, which is incompatible with v_2 = 7. Hence n is even. The 2-adic LTE gives v_2(3^n − 1) = v_2(3 − 1) + v_2(3 + 1) + v_2(n) − 1 = 1 + 2 + v_2(n) − 1 = 2 + v_2(n). Setting 2 + v_2(n) = 7 yields v_2(n) = 5, i.e., 32 | n and 64 ∤ n. Equivalent group-theoretic check: ord_{2^7}(3) = 32 and ord_{2^8}(3) = 64; thus 3^n ≡ 1 (mod 2^7) iff 32 | n, while 3^n ≡ 1 (mod 2^8) iff 64 | n, matching v_2(n) = 5.\n\n(5) For p = 11 and base 2, ord_{11}(2) = 10. Moreover, 11 is not a Wieferich prime to base 2, since 2^{10} ≡ 56 ≠ 1 (mod 121), so by order-lifting (odd p) we have v_{11}(2^{10k} − 1) = 1 + v_{11}(k). Therefore, 11 | 2^n − 1 iff 10 | n, and 11^2 ∤ 2^n − 1 iff v_{11}(n/10) = 0, i.e., 11 ∤ (n/10). Our conditions thus impose 10 | n and 11 ∤ (n/10). In particular, it suffices that 11 ∤ n.\n\nCombining (1)–(4), we obtain the exact prime-power content of n at 2,3,5,7:\n- v_2(n) = 5,\n- v_3(n) = 2,\n- v_5(n) = 2,\n- v_7(n) = 2.\nSo n = 2^5 · 3^2 · 5^2 · 7^2 · t with t coprime to 2·3·5·7. Condition (5) requires 10 | n (satisfied already) and 11 ∤ (n/10); taking t = 1 ensures 11 ∤ n and hence 11 ∤ (n/10). The least such n is attained at t = 1.\n\nThus the least positive integer satisfying all five conditions is\nn = 2^5 · 3^2 · 5^2 · 7^2 = 32 · 9 · 25 · 49 = 352800.\n\nFinal answer: 352800.",
    "final_answer": 352800
  },
  "verification_notes": "Deterministic plan to verify n = 352800.\n1) Prime-power content of n:\n   - Compute v2(352800) = 5, v3(352800) = 2, v5(352800) = 2, v7(352800) = 2, and confirm 11 ∤ 352800.\n2) Condition (1): v3(10^n − 1) = 4.\n   - Compute r4 = pow(10, n, 3**4) and check r4 == 1.\n   - Compute r5 = pow(10, n, 3**5) and check r5 != 1.\n   - This confirms 3^4 | (10^n − 1) but 3^5 ∤ (10^n − 1).\n3) Condition (2): v5(6^n − 1) = 3.\n   - Compute s3 = pow(6, n, 5**3) and check s3 == 1.\n   - Compute s4 = pow(6, n, 5**4) and check s4 != 1.\n4) Condition (3): v7(20^n − 1) = 3.\n   - Compute t3 = pow(20, n, 7**3) and check t3 == 1.\n   - Compute t4 = pow(20, n, 7**4) and check t4 != 1.\n   - Also optionally confirm n is even.\n5) Condition (4): v2(3^n − 1) = 7.\n   - Compute u7 = pow(3, n, 2**7) and check u7 == 1.\n   - Compute u8 = pow(3, n, 2**8) and check u8 != 1.\n6) Condition (5): exact divisibility by 11.\n   - Compute a1 = pow(2, n, 11) and check a1 == 1.\n   - Compute a2 = pow(2, n, 121) and check a2 != 1.\n7) Edge checks:\n   - Ensure the minimality: any proper divisor n' of n fails at least one valuation condition due to reduced v_p(n') for p ∈ {2,3,5,7}. A quick programmatic check can test divisors of the form n / p for p ∈ {2,3,5,7} that still keep divisibility by 10; at least one of the five constraints must fail.\nAll pow computations are fast (mod small prime powers) and scale as O(log n).",
  "feedback": {
    "design_strengths": [
      "Interlocks LTE for multiple primes with distinct branches (a ≡ 1 and a ≡ −1) and the delicate 2-adic case.",
      "Uses multiplicative order and non-Wieferich behavior to specify an exact divisibility at p=11.",
      "Single final integer answer with strong, modular verification steps."
    ],
    "improvements": [
      "Could integrate Zsigmondy’s theorem more centrally (e.g., an additional primitive divisor constraint) to raise conceptual load.",
      "Add a secondary CRT construction step with explicit residues to emphasize synthesis even more."
    ],
    "anticipated_llm_pitfalls": [
      "Mishandling the 2-adic LTE and forgetting the −1 adjustment.",
      "Assuming (Z/2^kZ)^× is cyclic and imposing impossible congruences (e.g., 5^n ≡ −1 mod 2^k).",
      "Ignoring the non-Wieferich check at 11 and erroneously concluding that 11^2 divides 2^n − 1 for all multiples of 10."
    ]
  }
}
